        // For $m_2$ to be the median of $C_2$, there must be at least $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ that are $\le m_2$ and at least $k_2$ elements in $C_2$ that are $\ge m_2$.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$. There are $n$ such elements.
        // Consider the elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$. There are $n$ such elements.
        //
        // If $m_1$ is the median of $C_1$, then $C_1$ must contain $m_1$ and $k_1$ elements smaller than $m_1$ and $k_1$ elements larger than $m_1$.
        // If $m_2$ is the median of $C_2$, then $C_2$ must contain $m_2$ and $k_2$ elements smaller than $m_2$ and $k_2$ elements larger than $m_2$.
        //
        // The total number of elements smaller than $m_1$ is at most $n-1$.
        // The total number of elements larger than $m_2$ is at most $n-1$.
        //
        // The $n$ smallest elements are $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$.
        // The $n$ largest elements are $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // If $m_1 < a_{n-1}$ and $m_2 > a_n$, then $m_2 - m_1 > a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // If $m_1 = a_{n-1}$ and $m_2 = a_n$, we found a partition with difference $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // What if $m_1$ and $m_2$ are both in the first half, or both in the second half?
        // Suppose $m_1, m_2 \le a_{n-1}$. Then $m_2 - m_1 \ge 0$.
        // But then $C_1$ and $C_2$ together would need $k_1+k_2+2 = n+1$ elements.
        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ (total $n$ elements) must be distributed.
        //
        // The minimum difference is indeed $a[n] - a[n-1]$.
        // This is a standard result for this type of problem.
        // The two medians must "cross" the middle point of the sorted array.
        // One median must be $\le a_{n-1}$ and the other must be $\ge a_n$.
        // If both medians were $\le a_{n-1}$, then $C_1$ and $C_2$ would collectively need $k_1+k_2+2 = n+1$ elements.
        // These $n+1$ elements would have to be chosen from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ (only $n$ elements available).
        // This is impossible.
        // Similarly, both medians cannot be $\ge a_n$.
        // So one median must be $\le a_{n-1}$ and the other must be $\ge a_n$.
        // Let $m_1 \le a_{n-1}$ and $m_2 \ge a_n$.
        // Then $m_2 - m_1 \ge a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // Since we showed a construction that achieves $a_n - a_{n-1}$, this is the minimum.

        std::cout << a[n] - a[n - 1] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

