        // Now we must check the parity condition: `s % 2 == (n+m) % 2`.
        // The number of straight moves for `d_candidate` is `s_candidate = k - d_candidate = k - (k - m + n) = m - n`.
        // So, we need to check if `(m-n) % 2 == (n+m) % 2`.
        // This is equivalent to checking if `(m-n) - (n+m)` is even.
        // `(m-n) - (n+m) = m - n - n - m = -2n`. This is always even.
        // So, `(m-n)` and `(n+m)` always have the same parity.
        // This means `s_candidate = m-n` always satisfies the parity condition.
        //
        // So, if `k >= m`, we can always achieve `m-n` straight moves and `k-(m-n)` diagonal moves.
